[1] China: National Health Commission, 83 512 total cases, 4634 deaths
Date: Sun 28 Jun 2020
Source: China National Health Commission [in Chinese, machine transl. abridged, edited]
http://www.nhc.gov.cn/xcs/yqtb/202006/4fab649916c14ba188d42e1ca86112d6.shtml


On 28 Jun 2020 (as of midnight 29 Jun 2020):
- 12 new cases of confirmed infections (5 imported cases, 3 in Sichuan province, 1 in Liaoning province and 1 in Shanghai municipality; 7 locally acquired cases, all in Beijing municipality), 4 new cases of suspected infections (all locally acquired in Beijing), and no deaths.
- A total of 1907 imported cases have been reported.
- 83 512 confirmed cases and 4634 deaths; 78 460 recovered and discharged from hospital; 762 119 close contacts with infected patients, and 7012 are under medical observation.
- 6 new asymptomatic cases (5 imported cases); 1 locally acquired asymptomatic case confirmed as symptomatic; 102 asymptomatic cases under medical observation (including 63 imported cases).
- 1199 cases in Hong Kong [an increase of 2 cases since 27 Jun 2020], 46 in Macau [same as 27 Jun 2020].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
and
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[The outbreak in Beijing continues with 7 newly confirmed cases attributed to the outbreak. The 1st case in Beijing was reported on 11 Jun 2020; as of 27 Jun 2020, there have been 318 cases reported from Beijing, 21 in Hebei, and 3 in Liaoning, most likely associated with this outbreak.

There were 6 newly confirmed infections in asymptomatic individuals and 1 new conversion from asymptomatic to symptomatic in the past 24 hours. Since 18 May 2020, there have been 25 cases of conversion from asymptomatic to symptomatic infections reported by China. More in-depth follow-up information on the ongoing outbreak in Beijing can be found in section [1] of COVID-19 update (262): China (Beijing) superspreaders, WHO, global 20200616.7473860.

Takeaway message: China continues to have importations of infected individuals with the SARS-CoV-2; many of whom are detected as asymptomatic at the time of positive PCR testing. The most likely scenario for the outbreak in Beijing was an asymptomatic infected individual had false negative PCR testing, and started a transmission chain that ultimately reached the implicated market which served as an amplifier via a superspreading event(s). A similar scenario that may well have occurred in Wuhan with the seafood market serving as an amplifier of the prior "silent" transmission of infection.

A map of China showing provinces can be seen at https://sacu.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/provmap.png, and a HealthMap/ProMED map is available at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7520447,155. - Mod.MPP]

