[In the past 24 hours, according to the report at the source URL, the tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in South Korea has increased by 42 cases with no new deaths, compared with 62 cases and no new deaths in the previous day (27 Jun 2020). The daily newly confirmed case count has been at or below 100 for 78 consecutive days. There were 30 locally transmitted cases: Gyeonggi (14), Seoul (6), Gwangju (3), Daegu (2), Daejeon (2), Busan (1), Incheon (1), and Jeonbuk (1), and 12 imported cases -- airport quarantine (5), Gyeonggi (2), Seoul (1), Gwangju (1), Jeonnam (1), Gyeongbuk (1) and Gyeongnam (1). There were 6 provinces reporting no newly confirmed cases.

According to data from the "ncov" website of the Ministry of Health and Welfare, the cumulative rate has been 9.4% (http://ncov.mohw.go.kr/).

The overall impression hasn't changed: Lifting of measures has been accompanied by increases in locally acquired infections through increasing clusters related to gatherings of people at employment (bringing it outside employment to contacts) and in houses of worship, and bars and clubs.

Tabular and graphic analyses of the situation in South Korea with the addition of the 62 newly confirmed cases are available at the English language page, notice 401 and 401 are analyses of the 61 cases confirmed yesterday (27 Jun 2020) including listings of current ongoing clusters. Three of the clusters are related to religious gatherings, 2 clusters are related to door-to-door sales, 2 are related to "gatherings, and 1 to a club meeting.

Importations came from https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030. Americas (3), Europe (1), Asia excluding China (18), Saudi Arabia (4), Turkey (3), Pakistan, Bangladesh, Kyrgyzstan (2 each), Kuwait, India, Kazakhstan, Indonesia, Malaysia (1 each).

Takeaway message: Importations continue to be a challenge, and gatherings whether social or religious are key foci for enlarging clusters.

A map of South Korea showing provinces can be seen at https://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/korea-south-administrative-map.htm and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7520447,195. - Mod.MPP]

